{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_pakula_ver02/data/sn84026749/00222254401/1927042201/0749.xml":{"full_text":"'CONTENDERS FOR HEAVYWEIGHT' RING TITLE DWINDLE\nI\u20ac A\nHEHL RING OPPONENTS\nNDTNS PLENTIFUL\nFOR TITLE NOW\nBy Gene Tunney\nWorld Heavyweight Champion\nWhen I won the title last September, the sporting experts saw\nplenty of business\u2014and prosperity\u2014ahead for me. For they com\nmented:\n\u201cNever in the era of the heavyweight division has any new cham\npion been confronted with so many formidable looking foemen. If\nTunney is a successful champion, he can fight about every six\nmonths, and keep busy until he is a gray-headed old man.\u201d\n\u201cBusiness\u201d did look good then.\nThere was a possible return match with Jack Dempsey in sight.\nThen there was Harry Wills, the great challenger, still challenging.\nThere was Jack Sharkey, and also Jim Maloney. At the time, there\nwap much talk about Harry Persson, Knute Hansen, Monte Munn,\nPaolino and Paul Berlenbach.\nAnd, likewise, there was quite a bit of conversation about Jack De\nlaney as \u201cthe man Tunney should fight.\u201d\nIt looked as if I had at least a half dosen profitable fights ahead\nof me.\nBut the situation has changed\u2014#\nradically\u2014and in a trifle more than\nsix months.\nOs the group of last September,\n\u25a0only 9 'Maloney, Sharkey and Demp\naey remain as contenders. All the\nothers have been elijniriated. And\nSharkey or Maloney will be effaced\nfrom the picture in May. That\nleavei ojily the winner and Demp\ns aey\u2014and Dempsey is still something\nof an uncertainty in the role of a<\n\u201coomebacker.\u2019\u2019\n\nNever before, in the history\nof the sport, has a group that\nembraced nearly a dosen seem\ning contenders, been reduced\nwith such startling rapidity.\nAnd that Is due largely to my\nI own suggestion for an elimina\ntion tournament to decide which\nwas the best man and the most\np dangerous of my opponents.\nAt\u2019the time I won the crown, I\nWas eager to fight every six months\n\u2014ls a real opponent loomed along\nthe Aprieon. For' fighting is my\nprofession, and the only way a cham\npion can mako big money is to\nfight. Yet, one fight a year, so\nlong- as I am champion, seems to\nbe the best I can hope for\u2014and I\nam pot so sure I can get into action\nas often as that.\nLong before September the.final\nbattle in the elimination will have\nbeen fought, and one man alone\nwill survive. That's the man I will\nbattle. Assuming that I whip him,\nFOR HIRE\nM. STEIN CO.\n\u2022\u25a0\u25a0f 7 x Taller/ i\n804-808 F StN. W.\nIf it\u2019s Auto\nG-L-A-S-S\nWE HAVE IT\nTARANTO WASMAN\n1017 New York Ave. N. W.\nV Franklin 6539\nnM \u2014-*1 O iy|\nV- i cEnume. t w\niJL y t austrauahvA I II\n1 KANGAROO I\nIv-\nfi Standing on Facts A\nUm*\nI I Australian Kangaroo shoe is one good illustration ft\nOi I I OW mu^l value can be built into a shoe for $6.60.\nEl- N\u00b0 other shoe manufacturer in U. S. A attempts to KJ\nJ! produce a shoe in this Quality to sell for $6.60. And W\nJit S some manufacturers charge more than twice $6.60 for JL\niQj a genuine Australian Kangaroo shoe. O\nMbf n\u2018 ie power of a National Institution, O\nJk concentrating its entire Factory Production on One fl.\nO Wbw yoortls up m this new Quality, shipping direct to its own Chain of Stores tQ\nISJ from Coast to Coast, and selling all Styles at One low H\nH gggg** Unstb vMth P r3 ce and One small profit, makes it possible to give W\nIk you greater Value and .more Style, for less money. Ab\njOj jit Sf&tlr iatUKi*9*l Sfrex. fQj\nA National Institution is now at your Service O\nJk FMm Camt to Cowt Ak\nRE GAL\u00ae SHOES\n\u00a33 915-917 Pennsylvania Ave. 1327 F Street N. W. U\nI 0 (Man's Exclwsivaly) (Man's and Women's) 11\nOPEN SATURDAY EVENINGS (0|\nI cannot expect any farther ring\naction for at least a year.\nFor, by defeating the winner\nof the elimination battles, I will\nbe beating the best man of the\npresent group. Certainly, if I\nwin from him, I hardly can ex\npect a promoter to send, mo\nagainst one of the men that was\neliminated along the way. There\nfore, I must wait until there ta\ni developed a really formidable\nfighter who looks good enough\nto beat me.\nSome think that by 1928 Delaney\nwill have added enough poundage\nand acquired enough strength to\ngive me a real battle. Maybe so.\nOthers think that Tommy Loughran,\nof Philadelphia, may be the man.\nA scattering few think that 1928\nmay find Young Stribling suf\nficiently formidable. And that may\nhappen.\nOn the other hand, none of the\nthree may develop sufficiently in\nthe public\u2019s mind for him to be\nfigured as a menace to a heavy\nweight champion's reign. In which\ncase I may be compelled to remain\nidle through 1928 unless some un\nknown develops in meteoric fashion\nwithin the next eighteen months.\nSo, the \u201cbusiness\u201d outlook\nIsn\u2019t quite so good as it was pic\ntured\u2014but the \u201cfault\u201d is mine.\nI could have done as other\nchampions have done picked\nmy foeman and kept on picking\nthem until I had gathered in a\nfortune meeting the \u201csoft ones.\u201d\nBut I wanted an elimination\nstaged so that I would be compelled\nto meet the best man. it has been\nstaged, and even if it knocks me\nout of a lot of \u201cbusiness,\" I will\nhave the comfort of knowing that\nnext September I will be meeting\nthe BEST of all the challenging\nheavyweights\u2014not a \u201csetup\u201d of my\nown choosing.\nRUNS IN THE FAMILY\nFour brothers, Harry, Willis,\nClyde and Hay Lamb, of Cedar\nRapids, lowa, are all athletic coaches\nat various high schools throughout\nthe State.\nPenny Ante\n(IHRbUfiH LFMDIb) f//A THAT'S A\nyou CHIPS \u2014you,\nCAM 6ET 'EM OFF \"A MA Kin'A You'Re .W/ \"e >T fcer|\nW banker! U OJ.FE STANy\nWHAT PID YOU f HER OWN I STAND BY V\nDo cuith That /why losses! /ano\nTen dollars you v\np(NMOUEY OLD J B ME >A|NT. V\nJ 6AY6 YOU MEANY. I OUT\nTHIS J A J, V. FOR\u2019 I\nafternoon; u I a\nJ' rJportT.\nI kfhjou) U)HAT\nK:\u00ab!>\u2014 yWL\n(P JI is/\ny-2.2\nIE TICKETS\nA PROBLEM\nFinding a needle in a haystack\nor driving a square plug in a\nround hole are no more problems\nthan the Yale athletic authorities\nhave in their annual task of de\nciding how best to divide 44,825\nseats at Yale Bowl among 38.299\ngraduates and undergraduates, who\nin theory are entitled to anywhere\nfrom one to 20 tickets for seats\nduring a football game.\nMortimer N. Bruckner, New\nYork banker, Is head of the\ncommittee that annually engages\nthe problem, and the committee\nhas decided that great restric\ntiOhs must still hedge the tickets\nin order to give every one a\nchance to see the football game.\nBut the committee thinks there\nis hope for more tickets without\nenlarging the bow!.\nThere are only 18,576 seats be\ntween the goal lines on Yale\u2019s side\nof the bowl. Behind the goals are\n311249 seats Yale has the right to\nuse, but who wants to sit behind\nthe goal posts? When another foot\nball season is under way, Yale prob\nably will have 5,900 undergraduates\nand about 37,000 graduates to pro\nvide with seats in the bowl.\nj WASHINGTON TIMES SPORTS\nATHLETIC CLUB\nLEAGUE\nFINAL ~k'ANDINGS\nW Pet Total\n52 29 .642 44,812\nT^. aU 51 30 62 4<531\nOrrtson \u00abo 41 ,4 #g 43,298\nISOmad\u00df \u00a32 49 395 42 281\nHu\u00abh Boniy 16 is at! 3\u00bb.47i\nTEAM KECOBDS\nSmlthhoid 634 ms\u20192o6 1017\nArlington 635 1814 1\u00ab2 914 547- G\nRecreation \u00ab43 1817 178 946 549 63\nh *P\u00bb 587 1694 185 832 535-69\nPrinters 688 1735 176 868 541.78\nOrrlson 623 1697 167 846 534 34\nGeorgetown 607 1687 172 776 520-56\nNationals 652 1692 171 763 520-20\nNomads 612 1696 167 767 521-80\nHugh Reilly u*3\u2019lo\u00bbo 12\u00bb -5\u00bb0 487-27\nSEASON\u2019S RECORDS\nHigh team set\u2014Recreation. 1817.\ngam ?~Nationals. 662. High\nindividual set\u2014McKltrick (Union Print\ners) 4u6. High individual game\u2014\nCowles (Union Printers). 164 High\nstrikes\u2014Tompris (Ahepa), 44